    "\n",
    "## The meaning of `*`\n",
    "\n",
    "1. In a declaration: `*` means 'this variable is a pointer'\n",
    "```c\n",
    "char *s = \"HI!\";\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "- Here `*` is just telling C: \"s is a pointer to a char.\"\n",
    "- This `*` is part of the type, not an operation.\n",
    "- `the pointer to char called \"s\", and \"s\" = address of \"HI!\"`\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "1. In an expression - `*` means \"go to that address and get the value\"\n",
    "```c\n",
    "printf(\"%c\\n\", *s);       // *s = 'H'\n",
    "printf(\"%c\\n\", *(s + 1)); // *(s+1) = 'I'\n",
    "printf(\"%c\\n\", *(s + 2)); // *(s+2) = '!'\n",
    "```\n",
    "- Here `*` is the dereference operator. It's an action.\n",
    "- It means: \"take the address s+1, go there, and pull out the value.\"\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- Using %s (prints a whole string)\n",
    "```c\n",
    "printf(\"%s\\n\", s);      // starts at 'H' → prints \"HI!\"\n",
    "printf(\"%s\\n\", s + 1);  // starts at 'I' → prints \"I!\"\n",
    "printf(\"%s\\n\", s + 2);  // starts at '!' → prints \"!\"\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "```python\n",
    "#include <stdio.h>\n",
    "#include <stdlib.h>\n",
    "\n",
    "int main(void)\n",
    "{\n",
    "    int *x = malloc(3 * sizeof(int));\n",
    "    if (x == NULL)\n",
    "    {\n",
    "        return 1;\n",
    "    }\n",
    "    x[0] = 72;\n",
    "    x[1] = 73;\n",
    "    x[2] = 33;\n",
    "    free(x);\n",
    "    return 0;\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "↓\n",
